:"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705179,"age":4,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705180,"age":7,"year":"1016","julianDay":2092146,"title":"Canut the Great","description":"As Aethelred, King of England died, his son, Edmund Ironside devised a truce with Danish King Canute. The truce divided the kingdom between the two but Edmund died shortly after and became King of England. Several years later, he also became king of Denmark.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnut_the_Great","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Cnut the Great","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705181,"age":26,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705182,"age":57,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes de FitzRichard was born in 1009, in Oxfordshire, England. She married Richard FitzScrope before 1040, in Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1076, in Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1009–1076":"1009–1076","1020–1067":"1020–1067","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1045–1100":"1045–1100","1048–Male":"1048–Surnud","about 1040":"umbes 1040","1066":"1066","About 1048":"umbes 1048","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1016":"1016","1048":"1048","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1045":"1045","1067":"1067","1100":"1100","before 1040":"enne 1040","1009":"1009","Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England":"Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1009–1076":"1009–1076","1020–1067":"1020–1067","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1045–1100":"1045–1100","1048–Male":"1048–Kuollut","about 1040":"noin 1040","1066":"1066","About 1048":"noin 1048","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1016":"1016","1048":"1048","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1045":"1045","1067":"1067","1100":"1100","before 1040":"ennen vuotta 1040","1009":"1009","Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Richard's Castle, 